1. Dictionary (dict)
In Python, this is the concrete implementation. It is a built-in data type. When you write my_dict = {"name": "Gemini"}, you are using a Python dictionary.
Unique Feature: Since Python 3.7+, dictionaries are officially ordered (they remember the order in which items were inserted).
Usage: This is what you will use 99% of the time in Python.

2. Hash Map
This is a conceptual/generic term used in computer science.
If you were coding in Java, you would literally use a class called HashMap.
In Python, when someone says "Hash Map," they almost always mean a Python Dictionary.
The "Hash" part: It's called this because it uses a Hash Function to turn your key (like the string "apple") into an index in memory, making lookups nearly instantaneous.

3. Hash Table
This is the underlying data structure.
Think of the "Hash Table" as the engine and the "Dictionary" as the car.
A Hash Table is the mathematical and architectural way of organizing data so that you can find any value in O(1) (constant) time. 

4. Associative Array
This is another theoretical term. It simply describes any data structure that associates a key with a value.
Dictionaries, Hash Maps, and Hash Tables are all types of Associative Arrays.

